In the 1800s there were many reasons for the people from different cultures to uproot themselves and to move the United States. All immigrants were needed to work to build and advance the world they moved to. Such jobs included working in the new factories, farming the land, constructing new buildings and homes, and to invent new things to help advance their culture and society. They're the ones who started what we live on today.      The countries who sent their people to the United States sent different numbers of people. The Germans made up the largest group of immigrants, with the Irish following. One-fourth of the population of Ireland gave up their country to go live in America. The reason they did this is because back in Ireland most crops had failed, especially the potato crop. That lead to a food shortage resulting to the deaths of more than 1 million people.     The European countries sent their people later in the 1800s. These countries includes Russia, Italy, Poland, Denmark, Sweden, and Hungary. In Europe the population had doubled, making it harder to find work. This happened between the years of 1750-1850. The extra people living there needed food, a home, and a good income. That made the idea of moving to America seem fit.     After a few years, in America industry grew and even more immigrants arrived. They had created the first railroad in the United States in 1869. This made moving resources such silver and lumber much easier. There was also a change on how quick information from different areas of the U.S. traveled. The redesign of the printing press made it easier and possible to print as many inexpensive books and newspapers as wanted. It also made new ideas available to more people. The telegraph was created in 1844 and the telephone in 1876, helping news travel even faster.      The move of many immigrants lead to new inventions, new land, and a mixed culture. There were even more immigrants that came to America that came to escape from violance, harsh conditions at home, to get a job, or to just make a new life. The immigrants came for more freedoms, to even escape their old life. All the immigrants helped make what we call the United States today.

There were also big advancements in technology. Some of these include trains, steamships, cars, telegraph, phone, and more. With steamships it did not take months to get to the Americas. With a train travelers could travel much more quickly than they would on a horse. With the new telephone, news could travel to other cities much more quickly.        In the middle 1800s there was a 'Gold Rush'. A gold rush is when people head some where to mine gold there. In 1849, 70,000 Americans traveled to California, in look for some gold. With these people there were also Chinese, and soon more Chinese started to move to America. The reason why the Chinese were moving to America was that there was much conflict and poverty in some places in China.        That was my paper on the middle 1800s through the early 1900s. Others came for religious freedom.       A total of 26 million immigrants arrived in the United States over a fifty year time period. Also the number of people in the U.S. from 1860-1910 increased. There were a lot of push and pull factors. Therefore, people started to become more aware of the world around them and with the ability to move long distances easier, they kept moving.       Another reason is that gold was discovered in 1848 along the American River. So, more than 70,000 hopeful adventurers arrived in California in 1849. Along with these Forty-Niners, were 325 men from China. More Chinese came the next year and the next year. Those 325 people who joined the Forty-Niners in 1849 were just the start of all that. By 1870, there were 63,000 Chinese in the U.S.       The number of people in the United States, who live in cities, the coal production, miles of railroad tracks, and number of daily newspapers increased from 1860-1910. Irish crops had failed causing the Irish immigration. The population of Europe doubled  during this time period leaving many homeless and starving. Jews came to America hoping to find religious freedom. By the end of a 50 year time span, 26 million people had arrived in America.       By the second half of the 1800s, there was a great change in industry and transportation. The first railroad that crossed America was completed in 1869. This made it easier to move lumber and silver from coast to coast. A trip to the U.S. would have normally taken months but new steam ships could move much faster. The invention of the telegraph in 1844 and the phone in 1867 made news travel much faster.       Gold was found in the American River in 1848 by a man named John Sutter. The news spread rapidly across the United States and the rest of the world as well. By January of 1849, 60 ships and thousand of over land travelers were headed to California. Among the '49ers were 325 men from China. The first wave of Chinese migrants came from Guangdong, a place on China's south coast. The government in China raised taxes and farmers who could not pay for their land had to sell their farms. At the time, the population was also growing rapidly. So the Chinese hoped to find their fortune in the California hills.       Millions of men and women worked very hard and made it to America. If they could do that imagine what we can do now. Culture is very important in America and always will be.

The homes were all taken so that meant that many Europeans came to America to avoid starvation.   Many came for the religious freedom that was given in America. The time of the 1800s was a great change in America. Industry grew and many immigrants had arrived in America. The Transportation had succeed. The first railroad ever  had crossed the United States was complete in 1869. People may travel on these trains too. This was true in Europe too. Travelers now could get on a train that would take them straight to a boat. A trip to America in earlier times would have taken months, but new steamships will make trip even faster. These advances in transportation made it more possible for more people to travel more easily.       In the 1800s, there were also rapid and important change in how quickly and widely information traveled. Steam power and the redesign of the printing made it possible to  print many in expensive books and newspapers. This made news and ideas available to more people. The invention of the telegraph in 1844 and telephone in 1876 only made news travel faster.           People became more aware of the world around them and with ability to move long distances easily, they moved more than ever before. The reasons they moved are often characterized as 'pushes' and 'pulls.' Pushes are those features of life that drive people from their homes. These include a harsh environment, wars and other conflicts, and poverty. Many of these push elements were made  worse by rapid increase in the number of people in Europe. Pulls are those features of life that attract people. These include jobs, wealth,opportunities, access to resources, and perceived freedoms.           Many of the European immigrants wanted to escape harsh conditions in Europe. Russian Jews left to escape prejudice and persecution , in the form of pogroms ___organized violent attacks. Southern Italians suffered from  high birth rates and farming losses due to lower prices. The tradition of leaving of family land to first-born male often left younger siblings landless. Hungarians, Greeks, Portuguese, and Armenians also moved. Immigrants hoped to make a new life for themselves and their families in the United States. You probably have heard people saying that America is a land of freedom. In the 1800s and 1900s, many people migrated from other countries to America. Many came during the Gold Rush in California to find gold. Others came to seek freedom from their own countries. Some main reasons why people came to America in the 1800s is because of their home country difficulties, America's freedom and oppurtunites, and jobs and money.        Many people left their birth country because of the difficulties they had. For example, the Irish left their country because of their potato crop failure, which caused millions of people to die. Another example includes when the Chinese in Guangdong left to find gold in California. In Guangdong, there were many fights and rebellions, high taxes, and overpopulation with food shortages because farmers had to sell their land due to the taxes. Also, Southern Italians left because of their tradition that the family's land goes to the firstborn male, leaving the other children landless.       In addition to that, people came for freedom and oppurtunities. They wanted to start a new life in America. For example, Jews left to get away from prejudice and persecution. Other people came to escape wars. People from Holland, Jews from Germany, Poland, and Russia came for religious freedom, because in European countries people mistreated them for their religion. Source #1 also stated: 'Most of the newcomers knew very little about America except that it was a land of freedom. But that's what they wanted: freedom and a chance to work.'       Lastly, people also came for new jobs and money. The overpopulation in Europe caused people to become homeless, hungry, and poor. These people came to America to get a job and avoid being hungry. The Chinese came for gold, fortune, and prosperity when they returned home. Because of all these people from other countries, industry grew greatly, allowing more and more jobs to be filled and taken. Advances that America developed, such as transportation with the railroad and trains, steam power, the telegraph, and the telephone, also attracted people.        America was a land of refuge, freedom, and money to these immigrants. Many people came to escape harsh conditions in their home countries, while others came for more oppurtunities and a new life. Still, many others came for jobs and fortune. Without these advantages that America had in the past, it probably may have never become the land that we know of today.

During the 1800s, working people who could build, farm, or invent came to America in ship after ship after ship. And just in time! With all the new technology in the 1800s there was plenty for them to do. They were needed to work in the new factories, to farm and build on the land, and to invent things. Immigrants did all that.                     Germans made up the largest single group of immigrants in the 1800s. Next to the Germans, the Irish were the largest immigrant group. Before the American Civil War in the 1860s, one-fourth of the whole population of Ireland came to America. (That was 1.7 million Irish men, women, and children.) Immigration was a big deal in the 1800's.  People from all different places moved to America for many reasons.  Some for freedom, others because the things that were waiting for them back at home were unbearable.  Even some came for the mere reason that there might be gold and riches at the end of their journey.  Everyone had a different story, everyone had a different reason, but they all came came together in the end in America.         There were many different people, and many different reasons people immigrate.  One reason people would immigrate is the fact that they wanted religious freedom.  For example, people from Holland and Jews from Germany, Poland, and Russia all came because there at home lives were unbearable.  Another reason people might immigrate to America is because they have to.  For example, in Ireland, the irish were desperate.  There crop had failed, and there was a extreme shortage of food.  More than one million people died of starvation.  So for the Irish, all they wanted was a place where they could eat.         Usually, there was two kinds of immigration.  They were called the push and pull factors.  A push factor is a factor that forces you to leave your home land. One example of a push factor is a lack of resources they have at there home land.  For example, in Ireland, there crop failed and everyone was starving for food.  This is an example of a push factor.  The other kind of immigration, a pull factor, is a little bit different.  A pull factor is when a person sees something appealing in another place and decides to immigrate because of it.  An example of pull factor is gold, a job, of freedom.  For example, the Jews wanted freedom, and they knew America had it.  That is why they immigrated.     Everyone has there own choices and beliefs.  That is why immigration if different for everyone.           One very big pull factor in history was the California Gold Rush.  This is when John Sutter in 1848 found gold on his property in California.  Word got around about the discovery, and people got excited.  Thousands of immigrants moved to California in search of finding some of this highly coveted gold.  Many Chinese arrived also.  The taxes were going up where they lived, and they were hoping to find some money.  There dream was to find a ton of gold, and come home with a pile load of riches.  Also, another reason the Chinese arrived was because the people in China did not have enough rice to feed its people, especially when the floods destroyed the crops.           As you can see, every person has a different reason for immigrating.  Some for freedom, others for money, and some just to escape the hardships of everyday life.  Some didn't even have a choice.  This is what makes immigration so unique.  Not two people are the same.  Between push and pull factors, and larger reasons to immigrate, like the California Gold Rush, between 1860 and 1910,  it went from 31,513,000 people living in the United States to 92,407,000 people.  Also, in 1860 4,096,753 people were born out of state and in 1910, 13,344,545 people were born out of state.  This was all because the immigration of our people.

Before the American Civil War in the 1860s, one-fourth of the whole population of Ireland came to America! That's 1.7 million men, women, and children! But guess what, they kept coming, during and after the war! The Irish were desperate for a new place to live things in Ireland weren't as good as you would think. For Ireland more than 1 million people died from starvation.       In the later 1800s, people started coming from all over the European countries. They had not sent many people to America before.For example Russia,Italy,Poland,Denmark,Sweden and Hungary. The population of Europe doubled between 1750 and 1850. All of those extra people needed homes,food, and jobs. There just didn't seem to be enough of them in Europe. Many Europeans came to America to find work and avoid hunger. The transportation improved, the first railroad had been put up, industry grew, and many immigrants arrived. As the transportation improved that meant easier ways to cross over to America. In the 1800s, there was also rapid and important change in how quickly and widely information traveled. Steam power and redesign of the printing press made it possible to print many inexpensive books and newspapers. This made news and ideas available to people all over! In 1844 the invention of the telegraph and telephone in 1860 made it even easier for news to travel.       In 1848 along the American River in California, on the property of a man named John Sutter came a new wave of people. John tried to keep it a secret but it didn't last long. That was the start of the Gold Rush. By January 1849, 60 ships and thousands of overland travelers were headed for California. It had begun. More than 70,000 hopeful adventurers arrived in California. Among these 'Forty-Niners were 325 men from China. Most of the first wave was Chinese men coming from Guangdong, an area on China's south coast. They were fleeing from conflicts and poverty.       The American population and Industrial growth from 1860-1910 was booming! The number of people in 1860 was almost 32 million! You wouldn't believe it but in 1910 it was past 90 million! Everything had grown, people in cities, people born outside of the U.S., coal production, railroad tracks, and the number of newspapers! That is the history of the United States.

The History Of Immigration In America   By Jeremiah Williams                   Welcome to America! America in the 1800s was one of the most immigrated to country in the world! During this time period about 26 million people came to America. However, almost all of them came for different reasons. With everyone coming there must of been something to do! Immigrants did almost everything during the 1800s. This time period is very important to our history and could be important to our future.                    In the 1800s, millions of people came to the U.S. Many people came from different country to run away from things or to come for a better life. The German people made up the biggest group of immigrants. Most Germans left to get away from the war in Europe and just to live easier. Next to the Germans, the Irish were the biggest group. Overall, 1/4 of all of Ireland's population left to come to America! That was 1.7 million people in just the 1800s! The Irish people were desperate to survive. Their potato crop had failed as well as most of their other food. Other people came to have religious freedom. A lot of Jews from Germany, Poland, and Russia came to escape the terrible treatment of their home countries. All these people came for a reason and needed a place to work and live, what did they do when they got there?                    In the 1800s, 26 million people came to work and live. What exactly did they do? Most of them didn't have an education, so they became the builders and farmers. But some of them did have an education, so they became the inventors, politicians, and teachers. Another group of workers became miners and went as fast as they could to the California Gold Rush. A lot of these miners came from China, especially Guangdong. A lot of the Chinese people came to avoid war and poverty. Guangdong was involved in 2 wars between China and Britain, as well as many rebellions against the government and endless debt and taxes.This exciting news about gold spread though China like wildfire in a dry prairie. By 1870, over 63,000 Chinese people were in the U.S. Even though they could be found through out the country 77% of them were found in California. 70,000 people came from all over the world to California to try to strike it rich.                 In conclusion, many, many, people immigrated to the United States. Some came for jobs, others for freedom, but they all came with the idea of having a better life, and think about it if they didn't come our past, present, and future would never be the same.

Draft   Germans made largest group of immigrants Irish were next biggest group came because of starvation, more than one million people died  people from Russia, Italy, Poland, Denmark, Sweden, and Hungary came because the population had doubled there weren't enough jobs, food, and homes for them some came for religious freedom (Jews) from Holland, Germany, Poland, and Russia 26 million people arrived in United States over a 50 year period transportation improved, made it easier for people to travel to the states used to take months, now takes a short period of time invention of telegraph (1844) and telephone (1876) made news travel faster Russian Jews left to escape prejudice left to have new life in America Gold Rush brought people over 325 Chinese men came, then more the next year, and so on fleeing from conflicts and poverty (war) rebellions against government   called California Gam Saan, (Gold Mountain)       Rough Draft       In the 1800's population in America increased by thousands. Immigrants from all over the world came for many reasons: money, a new life, or religion. Many opportunities were available ion America and many people wanted to take it.       Germans made up the largest group of immigrants in the 1800's. The second largest group of immigrants were the Irish. They came because their crops were failing (potato crop) and they were dying from starvation. More than one million people in Ireland (men, women, and children) died from starvation. People from Russia, Italy, Poland, Denmark, Sweden, and Hungary came. The population in Europe had doubled therefore making it difficult for people to live. There weren't enough jobs, houses, or food for them to survive making them come to America. Many people also came for religious reasons. People from Holland, and Jews from Germany, Poland, and Russia came because they were being mistreated. In all, over 26 million people came to America over a 50 year period.      Another reason why people came to America was because of the change in technology. The first railroad was built in 1869 making it easier for people to travel from place to place. They would also move lumber and silver using the train. Transportation took from a few months to a short period of time. The telegraph, which was made in 1844 and the telephone, which was made in 1876, made communication and news easier for people. Russian Jews left and came to America to escape prejudice. A lot of people came to start a new life in America, so they can have a fresh start.       Gold! Gold! People rushed to California and started the Gold Rush. In 1848 someone found gold on a person named John Sutter's property. News spread like a wildfire attracting people like bees attracted to honey. The people who came were known as the Forty-Niners. Among these Forty-Niners were 325 Chinese men. More Chinese came year after year. They came to escape conflicts in the government and poverty. If they found gold they would go back to China as a hero. They nicknamed California Gam Saam, 'Gold Mountain.' The Chinese who arrived in California were just the start. The next year more people came, and so on so forth. 77% of the Chinese were found in California out of the whole United States.       As you can see, the 1800's played a huge role in America's history. Population increased. People from all over the world truly make America, without them, where would we be? Along the American River in California, gold was founded in 1848 on the property of a man named John Sutter. Mr. Sutter tried to keep his discovery a secret but soon enough the rumor had soon reached San Francisco, and hundreds of people left to find there riches. Then soon later on the rumor spread to the rest of the U.S. By January of 1849, 60 ships and travelers were headed for California. That is when the California Gold Rush had started.           Over than 70,000 travelers arrived in California in 1849. Along with this was the 'Forty-Niners' 325 men from China. After that more and more Chinese came the next year, and the next year. Like the other travelers the Chinese were also hopeful of finding there riches too.           Most of the Chinese migrants came from Guangdong. In the middle of the 1800s, Guangdong was involved with two wars between Britain and China.  With that the population of the Guangdong was increasing quickly.           Soon the people became hopeless of the thought of finding the riches they long for. They soon called it the Gam Slaan. To them it felt like a dream that would never happen. Like a long lost Fairy Tale. But they would not give up. In 1849 for the 325 Chinese who joined the gold rush it was just the beginning. It then came to 2,716 in 1851, and 20,026 in 1852. By 1870, there were 63,000. They played a criticcal part in building the first transcontinental railroad. Even thought they could be caught or seen through out the country, 77% of them were in California.           Adapted by Rebeca Stefoff, Journey to Gold Mountain: The Chinese in 19th-Century America (MY: Chelsea House Publishes, 1994) pp. 17-19, 21.

The Reason For Immigration             Over the past two hundred years, millions of immigrants came to America. Why did these people come? What caused them to abandon their homeland and travel for miles to come here? Ever since the 1800's,  immigrants have come to America because of 'pushes' and 'pulls.' 'Pushes' are generally bad things that force immigrants out of their country, such as food shortages. 'Pulls' are usually things that attract immigrants and make them want to come. Many times these things are related; if something bad happens in one's homeland, they want to get away and from in search of something better. These people thought of America as a land of freedom.            The majority of the people who came to America came because of 'pushes' that led them to abandon their homeland. Over 1.7 million Irish came to the U.S., desperate to leave their country because famine and losses of crops and lives. That's about one fourth of the total population of Ireland. Jews from Russia, Germany, Poland, and other countries left because of prejudice and persecution in the form of organized violent attacks. Italians suffered from high birth rates and farming losses due to lower prices and traditions. Also, the Chinese came because of conflicts, feuds, poverty, and high taxes. Many of these poor foreigners could not survive the harsh conditions of their homeland.            Though many of these people came to America because of 'pushes,' some came because 'pulls.' Chinese immigrants came to California after hearing wonderful tales about gold found in the mountains near San Fransisco. They thought they could make their fortunes in Gam Saan, or Gold Mountains, and them returned to China with much wealth. The Jews not only came to America to escape their country, but also to gain religious freedom. In general, many people from Europe, Asia, and other places came from freedom, homes, and the ability to get a job.                Different ethnic groups from various parts of the world came to America because of 'pushes' and 'pulls.' Some 'pushes' were food shortages, religious discrimination, poverty, and loss of jobs. Examples of 'pulls' were the right to gain freedom and the ability to get good jobs. This is why our country is now composed of strains from many different parts of the world, and why California is such a cosmopolitan state. America is and will always be known as the land of freedom.

In the 1800s, many people were suffering in their home countries, so many decided to come to America. They didn't know much about America, but they knew it was a land of freedom, and that is what they wanted, freedom and a chance to work.        People from Germany made up the largest group of immigrants in the 1800s. After the Germans, the Irish were the largest immigrant group. One-fourth of the whole population of Ireland came to America. The Irish were desperate because in Ireland crops had failed, more than 1 million people died of starvation in Ireland.        In the later 1800s, people from Russia, Italy, Poland, Denmark, Sweden, and Hungary came to America to find work and to avoid hunger. Other people from Germany, Poland, and Russia came to America for religious freedom, but still others came to escape wars that made life unstable, difficult, and unpredictable. In total, about 26 million immigrants came to the United States over a 50 year period.        During the second half of the 1800s, industry grew and many immigrants arrived on America. Also, transportation improved. In 1869, the first railroad in the United States was completed. Travelers could now catch a train that would take them right to a boat. Usually, a trip to America would take months, but with new steamships the trip was made faster. This made it a lot easier for immigrants to come to America.        In conclusion, although immigrating to America was a difficult journey in the 1800s, many people uprooted themselves and moved here.
